---
description: When the user wants to stress-test a plan or feature idea, sharpen terminology, or resolve design decisions through Q&A before writing code.
alwaysApply: false
---

Interview the user relentlessly about every aspect of the plan. Walk down each branch of the design tree, resolving dependencies one at a time. Ask one question at a time with your recommended answer. Explore the codebase instead of asking when facts can be verified.

- Sharpen fuzzy language — propose a canonical term when the user uses vague or overloaded terms
- Challenge against prior decisions in `design.md` if it exists
- Stress-test with concrete edge-case scenarios
- Cross-reference claims against code; surface contradictions

Capture resolved decisions immediately in `./docs/<feature-slug>/design.md` (canonical vocabulary table, decisions with rationale, edge cases, Q&A summary). State the slug first so the user can correct it.

As domain relationships, flows, and states become clear during Q&A, add Mermaid diagrams (or ASCII for simple structures) to a Visualizations section in design.md — don't wait until the end. Use `erDiagram` for entities, `sequenceDiagram` for request flows, `stateDiagram-v2` for state machines, `graph TD` for component boundaries. Skip a diagram if it would just restate the vocabulary table.

When design is complete, summarize decisions and automatically proceed to the PRD phase (to-prd).
